rule "rogyb-harness-required" {
  name = "ROGYB Harness Required"
  type = "mechanical"
  scope = "project"
  enforcement = "warning"

  harness {
    command = "go test ./..."
    timeout = "5m"
  }

  section "red" {
    text = """
Write a failing test that captures the exact behavior you want. The test must fail for the right reason — it proves the feature is absent or the bug is present. No code changes yet."""
  }

  section "orange" {
    text = """
Instrument the code path with logging, tracing, or metrics before making the fix. Orange is failure observability — add sensors so you can see exactly where and why the test fails. The fix has not landed yet; you are making the failure visible."""
  }

  section "green" {
    text = """
Write the minimum code to make the failing test pass. No more, no less. The test goes green; the feature works or the bug is fixed. Correctness is proven by the harness."""
  }

  section "yellow" {
    text = """
Instrument the success path with logging, tracing, or metrics after the fix. Yellow is success observability — add sensors that confirm the fix is working in production, not just in the test. If Orange asked 'can I see the failure?', Yellow asks 'can I see the fix holding?'"""
  }

  section "blue" {
    text = """
Refactor for quality. Clean up duplication, improve naming, simplify structure. No behavior changes — the tests must still pass. Blue is also where you tune Orange and Yellow output — keep the sensors that earn their keep and remove or downgrade the rest. Logs are important, but too many are dangerous: excessive logging can cause inode starvation, disk pressure, or leak sensitive data into long-lived stores. Blue is the craft step: the code works (green), is observable (orange+yellow), and now it is clean and lean."""
  }

  when {
    artifact_kind = "contract"
    status = "draft"
  }

  when {
    artifact_kind = "contract"
    status = "active"
  }
}

